(1) House approves bipartisan bill aimed at bolstering nuclear energy [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/9e76e236-1aed-431d-a641-57d5a73620bf?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Rachel Frazin for The Hill
=E2=80=9CThe Atomic Energy Advancement Act restores American leadership in =
nuclear energy and technology which is critical to our economic and nationa=
l security. I=E2=80=99m proud to lead the most significant update to nuclea=
r energy policy in the United States in over a generation,=E2=80=9D Duncan =
said in a written statement on its passage.
On Wednesday evening, the House approved a bipartisan bill aimed at bolster=
ing the United States=E2=80=99 position in nuclear energy. The Atomic Energ=
y Advancement Act is the U.S.=E2=80=99s first major nuclear energy policy u=
pdate in over a generation. Like any major bill, there=E2=80=99s a ton goin=
g on in it, but at it=E2=80=99s core it accomplishes a few things.
Efficient and Predictable Licensing: Less red tape. Faster timelines. Strea=
mlined reviews. More building. Love to see it.
Advanced Nuclear Technologies: Accepting and supporting new advanced design=
ed in nuclear that are safer and more efficient. In addition, the bill aims=
 to modernize the NRC, particularly in the context of advanced nuclear tech=
nologies.
Taken together, this Act enhance the United States' competitiveness in the =
global nuclear energy market and maintains our leadership position in nucle=
ar. So a special shoutout to representative Jeff Duncan (the handsome fello=
w in the image above) for introducing this bill and getting it passed. Jeff=
, come on the pod man!
(2) Figure rides the humanoid robot hype wave to $2.6B valuation [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/42dc681d-b1b4-4e46-9546-15721b9a36c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Brian Heater for TechCrunch
The Bay Area-based robotics firm announced a $675 million. The Series B val=
ues the startup at $2.6 billion post-money. The lineup of investors is equa=
lly impressive. It includes Microsoft, OpenAI Startup Fund, Nvidia, Amazon =
Industrial Innovation Fund, Jeff Bezos (through Bezos Expeditions), Parkway=
 Venture Capital, Intel Capital, Align Ventures and ARK Invest.
We=E2=80=99ve written about Figure a few times over the past year, so we we=
re pumped to see the company announce its $675M Series B from about as heav=
y-hitting of an investor group as you can imagine. Bezos. Altman. Huang. Pr=
etty tough to beat that trio right now. Figure=E2=80=99s mission is to expa=
nd human capabilities through advanced AI and robotics and they=E2=80=99re =
planning on deploying autonomous humanoid robots to fill gaps in the labor =
economy. Given the massive Series B, you=E2=80=99d have to imagine we=E2=80=
=99re at most a few years out from Future starting to deploy these shiny fe=
llas at real scale.
The company also announced a partnership with OpenAI to develop next genera=
tion models for humanoid robots. Figure founder Brett Adcock called his hum=
anoid robot =E2=80=9Cthe ultimate deployment vector for AGI [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/cd4b5323-8c4f-4867-a03c-8b12e4532083?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=E2=80=9D The genius robots=
 are coming.=20
The goal is abundance. And robots will play a crucial role in achieving tha=
t goal over the coming years. Whether it=E2=80=99s humanoids like Figure or=
 smart business models like Formic=E2=80=99s [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/f799ac68-77e7-4ed4-93b6-986eb6ffa77f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], we=E2=80=99re going to see robots creativ=
ely destroying a lot of the ways of doing things we=E2=80=99re accustomed t=
o. That=E2=80=99s a good thing. We=E2=80=99ll have more time to do things t=
hat aren=E2=80=99t working in a warehouse, or cleaning bathrooms, or collec=
ting trash.
(3) The World's First Electric-Adaptive Jet Engine | Ian Brooke, Astro Mech=
anica [ https://substack.com/redirect/dba598c1-6942-4924-8aa4-0d586d4401b6?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Christian Kyle for First Principles
Friend of the newsletter Christian Keil [ https://substack.com/redirect/aad=
cb8c0-c487-4947-8deb-d70970773f45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] dropped the first episode of his new Youtube se=
ries First Principles. In this episode, he sits down with Ian Brooke, the f=
ounder of Astro Mechanica.=20
Astro Mechanica has invented a new kind of jet engine. That=E2=80=99s a mic=
 drop of a statement.=20
AM=E2=80=99s jet engine, unlike any existing engine, is efficient at every =
speed. That unlocks a bunch of new and interesting use-cases. According to =
Ian, the first use-case will be using the engine to get payloads to orbit d=
ramatically cheaper than today=E2=80=99s existing all-rocket systems. The w=
ay this would work is you take off from a runway, drop a payload, and then =
that payload launches itself into orbit. That second piece =E2=80=94 the pa=
yload launching itself into orbit =E2=80=94 could be made possible by Astro=
 Mechanica=E2=80=99s electric-adaptive jet engine.
Watch the whole video. Christian is so obviously enthusiastic about making =
these videos and Ian was just so obviously put on this earth to build thing=
s like an entirely new jet-engine. Fun to watch.=20
But wait, there=E2=80=99s more! Check out:
Ian=E2=80=99s tweet with a video of an older version of the engine, which g=
ot 5.5M views [ https://substack.com/redirect/8cd005fd-1c24-4d5f-8da9-68cff=
139f4c8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
]
Andrew C=C3=B4t=C3=A9=E2=80=99s thread [ https://substack.com/redirect/000d=
c8c4-089a-462d-b3cc-53a24a7a2c31?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] explaining the jet engine, business model, and h=
ow AM will deliver commercial flight 3x faster than anything that exists an=
d beat Boeing
(4) How First Contact with Whale Civilization Could Unfold [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/86e0498c-295e-483f-987b-2f236c805898?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ross Andersen for The Atlantic
Project CETI=E2=80=99s scientists will need to observe the whales for years=
 and achieve fundamental breakthroughs in AI. But if they=E2=80=99re succes=
sful, humans could be able to initiate a conversation with whales. This wou=
ld be a first-contact scenario involving two species that have lived side b=
y side for ages. I wanted to imagine how it could unfold.
Kevin Kelly=E2=80=99s post on X [ https://substack.com/redirect/384d3f95-08=
87-4b84-9f12-65e1f0cbec8e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] brought this Atlantic story to our attention. The gist =
of the story is that we=E2=80=99re getting pretty darn close to being able =
to communicate with animals. And the first animal we=E2=80=99ll likely be a=
ble to communicate with is the whale. The sperm whale to be specific. All o=
f this this is, in large part, due to advancements in AI-based acoustic ana=
lysis.
An interesting future to imagine is one in which we=E2=80=99re able to comm=
unicate with all animals, but at varying levels of clarity. I imagine whale=
s and dolphins and dogs will all have things to say worth listening to. And=
 I also imagine there=E2=80=99ll be a whole slew of animals that have much =
to say, but not much to say worth listening to. But either way, we=E2=80=99=
ll have tens of billions of new stakeholders =E2=80=94 each with their own =
voice =E2=80=94 and that will surely bring new ethical conundrums and chaos=
=2E Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong, I=E2=80=99m h=
ere for it, but it just might ge=
t noisy.
(5) =E2=80=98Epigenetic=E2=80=99 editing cuts cholesterol in mice [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/72bf8e95-cca7-4491-8bcd-85f81b5cc6ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Heidi Ledford for Nature
An alternative to genome editing [ https://substack.com/redirect/feb1fc95-8=
534-4d53-983a-5a441df4e921?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] can reduce the activity of a gene that affects cholest=
erol levels without changing the DNA sequence =E2=80=94 and does so for an =
extended period, according to a study1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/d149=
cfa5-f3dc-4af8-9f94-0da77b40aab4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in mice. Scientists achieved this effect by chan=
ging each animal=E2=80=99s =E2=80=98epigenome [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/65739140-f7c5-4211-a389-ef4e69175561?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=99, one feature of which is a colle=
ction of chemical tags that are bound to DNA and affect gene activity.
Anotha one in gene editing. Last week we covered MEGA-CRISPR, a new methodo=
logy that edits RNA instead of DNA, which reduces the risk of permanent gen=
etic changes. This week we have another alternative to CRISPR called =E2=80=
=9Cepigenetic editing.=E2=80=9D Epigenetic editing is a technique that modi=
fies the chemical tags on DNA, affecting gene activity without altering the=
 DNA sequence itself. Like MEGA, epigenetic editing avoids some of the risk=
s associated with traditional CRISPR gene editing and is part of a larger w=
ave of non-invasive gene therapy methods. You don=E2=80=99t want to make un=
intended and permanent changes to your DNA structure, and things like epige=
netic editing can help avoid that.
Alright, shifting from DNA to DND for now. That=E2=80=99s all for this week=
=2E
